<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900810-0117</DOCNO><DOCID>900810-0117.</DOCID><HL>   Enterprise Brief -- Safer Inc.:   Dispute Over Safety Claims   Is Settled With the EPA</HL><DATE>08/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><LP>   Safer Inc., Newton, Mass., said it agreed to settle adispute with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agencyconcerning promotional safety claims the closely held concernhas made about its biodegradable pesticides.   In July 1989 the EPA filed an administrative complaintagainst the company, charging that its literature violatedfederal laws prohibiting safety claims in pesticideadvertising. Safer argues that the laws were drafted beforerelatively benign pesticides such as its &quot;insecticidal soaps&quot;were available, and so are &quot;outdated&quot; and shouldn't apply toits products, which it has advertised as nontoxic.Furthermore, Safer noted, the EPA hasn't questioned thesafety of its products -- only the language used to promotethem.</LP><TEXT>   The company said that under its consent decree with theEPA, it will pay a $10,000 civil penalty and undertake aprogram of &quot;environmentally beneficial expenditures promotingthe safe use of pesticides.&quot; Safer added that it agreed tothe settlement to avoid &quot;costly and protracted&quot; litigation.</TEXT></DOC>